
	xvargs: variadic argument library for x86_64 programs

API
	* XVARG_SAFE: this macro, when defined at assembly time, enables
	bounds-checked access. xvargs_init then accepts two extra arguments
	(limit and default). When the internal offset reaches the limit,
	xvargs_next returns the default instead of reading past the stack.

	* xvargs_init: initialises the library with the caller's frame base.
	- rdi: caller's %rbp value (after `pushq %rbp; movq %rsp, %rbp`),
	      or %rsp saved before setting up the caller's own stack frame
	- rsi: (only with XVARG_SAFE) maximum number of arguments to read
	- rdx: (only with XVARG_SAFE) value returned once the limit is exceeded

	* xvargs_next: returns the next variadic argument in %rax. Reads from
	16(%rbx) for the first call, 24(%rbx) for the second, etc., where
	%rbx is the base stored by xvargs_init.

	* xvargs_fini: resets all internal state (saved rbp, offset counter,
	and safe-mode fields) to zero, making the library available for
	re-initialisation.

SET UP
	Arguments must be pushed onto the stack in reverse order (rightmost
	argument first), matching the System V AMD64 ABI. The caller's base
	pointer must be saved and passed to xvargs_init before the first
	xvargs_next call.

	                          # stack (low-to-high):
	pushq    $'C'             # | 'C' | <- rightmost (pushed first)
	pushq    $'B'             # | 'B' |
	pushq    $'A'             # | 'A' | <- leftmost  (pushed last)
	pushq    %rbp
	movq     %rsp, %rbp
	movq     %rbp, %rdi       # pass frame pointer
	call     xvargs_init
	call     xvargs_next      # %rax = 'A'
	call     xvargs_next      # %rax = 'B'
	call     xvargs_next      # %rax = 'C'
	call     xvargs_fini
	leave
	addq     $24, %rsp        # restore stack: 3 args x 8 bytes

	Failure to clean up the stack will leave %rsp misaligned and may crash
	the program on subsequent calls or on exit.

	For a complete example

	.section .text
	.globl _start
	_start:
		pushq   $254
		pushq   $134
		call    .tester
		addq    $16, %rsp
		movq    %rax, %rdi
		movq    $60, %rax
		syscall

	.tester:
		pushq   %rbp
		movq    %rsp, %rbp
		movq    %rbp, %rdi
		movq    $2, %rsi        # safe limit
		movq    $96, %rdx       # safe default
		call    xvargs_init
		call    xvargs_next
		call    xvargs_next
		call    xvargs_next     # past limit -> returns 96
		call    xvargs_fini
		leave
		ret

USAGE
	After xvargs_init, each call to xvargs_next reads the next 8-byte
	value from the stack. The stack layout relative to the stored base
	pointer (%rbx) is:

	  Offset   Contents              xvargs_next
	    0      saved %rbp            (not read)
	    8      return address        (not read)
	   16      arg0 (last pushed)    call 1 -> arg0
	   24      arg1                  call 2 -> arg1
	   32      arg2                  call 3 -> arg2
	   ...     ...

	Because the System V ABI pushes arguments right-to-left, the last
	value pushed corresponds to the leftmost (first) parameter in the
	C calling convention.

ERRORS
	xvargs has two fatal error conditions. In both cases the message is
	written to stderr (fd 2) and the process exits with code 1.

	  * "xvargs: cannot invoke two instances of xvargs at the same time"
	    Raised when xvargs_init is called while the library is already
	    initialised and xvargs_fini has not been called.

	  * "xvargs: safe-limit is not an invalid limit (limit < 1)"
	    Raised when XVARG_SAFE is defined and xvargs_init is called
	    with %rsi (the limit) set to zero or a negative value.

NOTES
	* Frame pointer requirement: xvargs depends on a valid %rbp frame
	  pointer to locate arguments on the stack. If compiled with
	  -fomit-frame-pointer, the caller must manually save %rsp before
	  setting up its own stack frame and pass that saved value instead.

	* Not re-entrant: xvargs uses a single set of static variables in
	  .bss. Only one caller may use the library at a time. Call
	  xvargs_fini before re-initialising for a subsequent call.

	* Stack cleanup: The caller is responsible for restoring %rsp after
	  the variadic call by adding 8 bytes per pushed argument, or by
	  popping into scratch registers.

	* Argument order: Arguments must be pushed in reverse order (
	  rightmost first). xvargs_next reads them left-to-right, matching
	  the natural C parameter order.

	* xvargs_fini: Always call xvargs_fini when done. It zeros all
	  internal state, allowing the library to be safely re-initialised.

	* Dependencies: tiny_pf (https://github.com/h0p3so/tiny-pf) uses
	  xvargs for its variadic argument handling.

	* Platform: x86_64 Linux only - uses write (syscall 1) and exit
	  (syscall 60) directly for error reporting.
